		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Fri, Feb 4th 9:40 AM2005 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/db/classes.html?class=8&mid=1097070111295686013&num=17&post=1&replyto=1107528006573715194"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a> | <a class="sm" href="/db/journal2.html?user=420982"><img border="0" src="/shared/user_journal.gif" border="0" height="12" width="17" /> User's Journal</a>   <a name=1107528006573715194></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=420982"><span id=>jchapin</span></a><b><span id=></span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />104 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=jchapin&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>1st. Killing the guards in GFay is a BAD IDEA!!! Since your a woodelf Druid im sure you know this.<br><br>2nd. Rotting, Kiting, Charm Kiting and Quading.<br><br>A) Rotting: Snare, root, DoT x 2. Med while the DoT's do their thing and reroot and DoT when necessary. This method is best used when kiting isnt an option do to adds or limited space. I use 2 DoT's as opposed to three because I've noticed three tend to break root more frequently but that can be debated.<br><br>B) Kiting: Snare, move to maximum casting range then DoT or nuke. (depending on which you prefer) Stay at maximum casting range and continue until mob is dead. (Obviously) Best used when adds aren't that much of a concern and you have enough room to move.<br><br>C) Charm kiting: First off, make sure your CHA is as high as possable as this controls your charm. Snare an animal then charm and buff it. Pull a mob with snare and kite it while your pet attacks the mob. For max XP break charm before the target mob dies then root (park) your ex-pet. Continue kiting the mob then kite your pet once the main mob is dead.<br><br>D) Quadding: Kiting x 4: A little tricky but once you get the hang of it it's easy. Snare 4 mobs (Works best with the same type of mobs due to differances in run speed) and group them together by running circles around them until they are on top of each other. (Will look like 1 mob but they are all their) Then use your AE nuke. (Green spell gem, lightning, outdoor only)<br>VERY IMPORTANT! Make sure you have enough mana to complete the quad. Last thing you want is 4 pissed off mobs coming after you while your OOM. 1 is bad enough. To do this check how much mana 1 cast of your AE nuke uses then figure out how many times you can cast it before you go OOM. (Dont forget about mana used for snares, the occasional root for adds and a heal or 2 because you will get hit once in awhile) Then find the mob you want to quad. Snare and cast your AE and watch how much damage you do to the mob. For example if you can cast your AE nuke ten times without going OOM you need to do at least 10% damage to the mob to complete the quad.<br><br>3rd. Solo XP.<br><br>A) Low - Mid 50's: Quanimbi's; Rot the fleshrippers, Turpta's and stonemite's. The fleshrippers hit hard and fast and the turpta's are way underconned so it depends on how your equiped. Stay away from the Fierce Cragwalker. He's named that for a reason. Cobalt scar; Kite or quad the drakes and wyverns but watch out for the named wyverns. I'f you get too many adds go to Great Divide and kill frost giants for awhile to raise your CoV faction. This can also be done in Keal Drakkel.<br><br>B) Upper 50's to mid 60's: Plane of Mischief; Charm a skunk and charm kite or just kite. Plane of Nightmare; Quad the ravens. Plane of Valor; Kite the razorfiends at the outer cave camp. Draniks Scar; Rot the nocs, dragorns, Kyvs and ukuns at the Bloodfields zoneline or the Nobles Causeway zoneline. Be extremly careful as the nocs and kyvs triple hit and proc for 450+ each hit. The ukuns can snare/root. Nobles Causeway; Kite the murkgliders but again be careful as some snare, some DoT, some do both and some don't do anything. Just luck of the draw. Dragons Necropolis-indoor zone; Rot the phase spiders. Some of the phase spiders will port you back to the zoneline so going past those 4 is pointless.<br><br>When camping zonelines be considerate of other players. If someone is on the otherside be sure to warn them of whats waiting on the other side.<br><br>I've found that quad Kiting is sometimes better XP than a group, just alot more work. Once you've goten comfortable with these methods sitting LFG for hours on end wont be so bad anymore. Hope this helps. Good luck and happy hunting.</p><br /><span class="sm">----------------------------</span><br />A good player will make a bad character look good.<br>A good character will NOT make a bad player look good. </td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td></tr></table>
